Comments_List:
 Course content (readings):
	Someone needs to say this: the 10-point investment framework is horrible. It is too far from being mutually exclusive comprehensively exhaustible because the categories have too much overlap. Prof MS doesnt allow students to use their own frameworks (and assumes we have none of our own, which is patronizing and untrue) e.g. buckets of different weights such as transaction probability and business projections should not be at the same level, projections as a giant category on its own beats the point of a framework, unmitigated risks+returns&terms+projections overlap too much. 10 points is too many to have at the highest level of a framework. The leadership framework is also funny and includes everything one does in life under the sun; it fails to define leadership because it considers everything leadership including a person's "methods" (such as Excel) and again has overlap with norms, culture, structure, behaviors - it felt like just an overfitting of a bunch of sociological buzz words
Course content (seminar):
	The class attracts a homogenous and testosterone-driven segment of Yale, which will always prevent it from being a superior Yale seminar: there was one girl in the class and few diverse students;
	Financial modeling is quite critical to the class yet the expectations for (even) fully trained summer analysts (IB/PE) are too high - yes you are expected to know modeling but the avg max level of prep is 1 summer of work and that is not enough for the breadth of situations encountered in this class (especially historical ones); Prof MS will describe several great ideas but it is unclear if anyone knows how to model them. On one hand, Prof MS de-emphasizes the modeling and on the other, he criticizes the way students did the modeling every class and stipulates the endless list of things that need to be modeled but provides no help to meet those expectations;
	The classes were too imbalanced  some weeks (growth equity) there was nothing to do and other weeks (PDI/Spark) there was too much;
Course assignments:
	Assignments are never checked so you never really improve; if your modeling was off, it will be off for the entire term and no one will care or notice. People will just make stuff up. For a high workload class you can get away with doing no work;
	The grading was opaque and no one knew his/her grades until too late in the semester. Unclear whether the quizzes were being graded and when/if there would be a pre-class quiz;
The final exam's last question (40% of the grade) was too random and felt like the professor's pet project since it had little to do with material taught in class. It felt like a corporate finance fun fact/brainteaser question with no answer. The lack of public information made it rather pointless;
Improvements: plan the class time and structure better (waste less time), encourage more debate and discussion as with real investments (don't espouse unchangeable truisms all the time), respect the students and cut the subtle racism (e.g. with the international Chinese student), give more feedback and provide some financial modeling advice (outside class if necessary), explain complicated corporate finance concepts more systematically
